---
// Yellow Legal Pad — Stacey's site, single page.
//
// This is Pass 310 atmosphere-only scaffold. Real copy arrives in
// Pass 312-314 once Stacey provides it. Placeholder text below is
// tonally aligned but DELIBERATELY GENERIC so it doesn't feel like
// finished writing — the page should look correctly empty until
// Stacey's actual words land.
//
// 7 sections, linear scroll, in the order Pass 308 §2 specified:
//   1. reassurance
//   2. story (Grampy + yellow legal pad origin)
//   3. philosophy
//   4. who it's for
//   5. process clarity
//   6. packages
//   7. invitation
//
// Composition rules being honored:
//   - "Printed not engineered" — document composition, not app
//     composition. Plain HTML, very few class names.
//   - "Slightly imperfectly human" — section padding deliberately
//     varies. Reassurance gets generous top space; Story has
//     longer measure for narrative; Packages tighter to feel
//     editorially organized.
//   - Reduce-motion respected throughout.
//   - Zero React. Zero islands. Zero client:* directives.
//   - One IntersectionObserver tucked at the bottom — sections
//     fade in once when first scrolled into view. Single property
//     (opacity). Under 400ms. Falls back to "always visible" if
//     JS disabled or reduce-motion preferred.
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
    <meta name="description" content="Yellow Legal Pad — financial coaching with Stacey. A quiet conversation, without judgment." />
    <title>Yellow Legal Pad — Stacey [last name TBD]</title>
    <link rel="icon" type="image/svg+xml" href="/favicon.svg" />
    <!-- No preconnect to font CDNs; fonts are bundled via Fontsource
         and ship with the build. Privacy + speed. -->
  </head>

  <body>
    <!-- Tiny inline script: only purpose is to add a flag class so
         the CSS knows JS is available. If this script never runs,
         the .reveal-on-scroll sections render at opacity 1 by
         default — i.e. the page works fully without JS. -->
    <script is:inline>
      document.documentElement.classList.add("js-enabled");
    </script>

    <main>
      <!-- ======================================================
           1. REASSURANCE
           Above the fold. Permission moment. The reader should
           leave this section already breathing slightly easier.
           ====================================================== -->
      <section class="section reveal-on-scroll" aria-labelledby="reassurance-title">
        <div class="column">
          <h1 id="reassurance-title">
            <!-- Placeholder. Stacey's actual opening will go here.
                 Likely something like "You're in the right place."
                 — but DO NOT WRITE that here; it must be hers. -->
            [Reassurance opening — Stacey's voice]
          </h1>
          <p>
            [One short paragraph that does the same emotional work
            as the welcome mat. Plain language. No optimization
            energy. Reads like Stacey speaking.]
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ======================================================
           2. STORY
           Grampy + the yellow legal pad origin. This is the most
           distinctive content asset in the site; it has its own
           wider measure for narrative.
           ====================================================== -->
      <section class="section reveal-on-scroll" aria-labelledby="story-title">
        <div class="column-wide">
          <h2 id="story-title">[Story heading — likely "About the name" or similar]</h2>
          <p>
            [Grampy paragraph 1 — the legal pad, the conversation,
            what it taught.]
          </p>
          <p>
            [Grampy paragraph 2 — what carries forward into Stacey's
            practice today.]
          </p>
          <p>
            [Optional paragraph 3 — bridge into Stacey's own voice.]
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ======================================================
           3. PHILOSOPHY
           "Wash a ziplock bag so you can fly first class."
           "You are not financially unintelligent — you are
           financially underserved." Three-beat rhythm:
           reassurance / practical / permission.
           ====================================================== -->
      <section class="section reveal-on-scroll" aria-labelledby="philosophy-title">
        <div class="column">
          <h2 id="philosophy-title">[Philosophy heading]</h2>
          <p>
            [Reassurance beat — "this is understandable."]
          </p>
          <p>
            [Practical beat — concrete framing. The ziplock-bag
            quote belongs here, in Stacey's exact phrasing.]
          </p>
          <p>
            [Permission beat — "you are not financially
            unintelligent. You are financially underserved." —
            Stacey's exact phrasing.]
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ======================================================
           4. WHO IT'S FOR
           Audience self-recognition. Plain prose, not a feature
           grid. Reader sees themselves and feels safe.
           ====================================================== -->
      <section class="section reveal-on-scroll" aria-labelledby="audience-title">
        <div class="column">
          <h2 id="audience-title">[Who this is for]</h2>
          <p>
            [Paragraph that names who Stacey works with — likely
            individuals, couples, families. Plain language. No
            ICP-style bullet list.]
          </p>
          <p>
            [Paragraph that names what they're often carrying —
            quiet financial shame, intimidation, exhaustion.
            Without naming it harshly.]
          </p>
          <p>
            [Optional paragraph that gently affirms: you don't
            need to have it figured out before you arrive.]
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ======================================================
           5. PROCESS CLARITY
           What a clarity session is. "Three specific things."
           Demystifies before asking. Reads like a calm
           explanation, not a sales pitch.
           ====================================================== -->
      <section class="section reveal-on-scroll" aria-labelledby="process-title">
        <div class="column">
          <h2 id="process-title">[What a session looks like]</h2>
          <p>
            [Paragraph framing what to expect — conversational,
            unhurried, no homework before arriving.]
          </p>
          <p>
            [Paragraph naming the "three specific things" or
            equivalent concrete moves Stacey makes during a
            session. Stacey's exact phrasing.]
          </p>
          <p>
            [Paragraph closing the loop — what you leave with.
            Likely: clarity + a next small step + permission.]
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ======================================================
           6. PACKAGES
           Editorially organized comparison. Equal visual weight
           per package. NO "BEST VALUE", NO "RECOMMENDED",
           NO aggressive pricing hierarchy. Reader concludes from
           prose what fits them; the design does not push.
           ====================================================== -->
      <section class="section reveal-on-scroll" aria-labelledby="packages-title">
        <div class="column-wide">
          <h2 id="packages-title">[Working together]</h2>
          <p>
            [Brief framing paragraph — "here are the ways we can
            work together, calmly." Stacey's voice.]
          </p>

          <!-- Package list — semantic, not a card grid. -->
          <article style="margin-top: 2.5rem;">
            <h3>[Package 1 name]</h3>
            <p>[Package 1 description — what it is, who it's for, what's included. Plain language. No "BEST VALUE" badge.]</p>
            <p class="caption">[Optional: cadence, pricing if Stacey wants it visible. Pricing is OPTIONAL at v1; many concierge practices gate pricing behind the discovery call.]</p>
          </article>

          <article style="margin-top: 2.5rem;">
            <h3>[Package 2 name]</h3>
            <p>[Package 2 description.]</p>
            <p class="caption">[Optional cadence/pricing.]</p>
          </article>

          <article style="margin-top: 2.5rem;">
            <h3>[Package 3 name — if applicable]</h3>
            <p>[Package 3 description.]</p>
            <p class="caption">[Optional cadence/pricing.]</p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ======================================================
           7. INVITATION
           Soft call-to-action. "The second best time is today."
           Booking link or contact form. NO transactional CTA
           language ever — see Pass 309 §4.2 + relay #35
           banned-phrase lists.
           ====================================================== -->
      <section class="section reveal-on-scroll" aria-labelledby="invitation-title">
        <div class="column">
          <h2 id="invitation-title">[Invitation heading]</h2>
          <p>
            [Closing paragraph in Stacey's voice. "The second best
            time is today" or equivalent. Soft, conversational,
            unhurried.]
          </p>

          <p style="margin-top: 2.5rem;">
            <!-- The CTA. ONE link. Conversational language only.
                 If Stacey already has Calendly, this is her
                 Calendly URL. Otherwise mailto: works fine
                 at v1. -->
            <a href="[CALENDLY_URL_OR_MAILTO]">Book a Discovery Call</a>
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ======================================================
           Footer — quiet acknowledgement, no marketing footer.
           ====================================================== -->
      <footer class="section" style="padding-top: 4rem; padding-bottom: 4rem;">
        <div class="column">
          <p class="caption">
            Yellow Legal Pad &middot; Stacey [last name TBD]
            <!-- Optional: small acknowledgement of Grampy. -->
          </p>
        </div>
      </footer>
    </main>

    <!-- Tiny IntersectionObserver — the only "JS" on the page.
         Adds .is-visible to .reveal-on-scroll sections when they
         first enter the viewport. Single property fade. If
         IntersectionObserver is unavailable (very old browsers),
         everything is visible by default.

         Per Pass 309 §7: this is the ONLY motion permitted at v1.
         If this script ever grows beyond ~15 lines or starts
         coordinating multiple effects, that is implementation
         drift — flag it.
    -->
    <script is:inline>
      (function () {
        if (typeof window === "undefined") return;
        if (typeof IntersectionObserver === "undefined") return;
        var prefersReduced = window.matchMedia &&
          window.matchMedia("(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)").matches;
        if (prefersReduced) return;

        var io = new IntersectionObserver(
          function (entries) {
            entries.forEach(function (entry) {
              if (entry.isIntersecting) {
                entry.target.classList.add("is-visible");
                io.unobserve(entry.target);
              }
            });
          },
          { rootMargin: "0px 0px -10% 0px", threshold: 0.05 }
        );

        document.querySelectorAll(".reveal-on-scroll").forEach(function (el) {
          io.observe(el);
        });
      })();
    </script>
  </body>
</html>
<style is:global>
  @import "../styles/global.css";
</style>
